Reasoning: The paper proposes a broader theory for analyzing the intrinsic difficulty of fully general interactive behaviors, using tools from concurrency theory. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category, which deals with the use of logic and formal methods in computer science. Additionally, the paper uses CCS-like processes to implement behaviors, which suggests that it may also belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category, which deals with the design and implementation of programming languages. The paper also deals with the execution of behaviors on a multiprocessor machine, which suggests that it may belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Furthermore, the paper deals with the analysis of behaviors, which suggests that it may also belong to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the use of labelled transition systems, which suggests that it may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category, which deals with the design and analysis of algorithms and data structures.
